You are reviewing the Supabase migration below for cross-tenant leakage via a join table that lacks its own RLS. Per-tenant model: each `projects` row belongs to one user; `project_collaborators` is the many-to-many join. Audit the policy posture across BOTH tables (follow-the-data discipline) and produce: (1) per-table posture table covering BOTH `projects` AND `project_collaborators` (silent omission of the join table is the failure mode this audit is designed to catch); (2) gaps with severity; (3) migration-shaped remediation enabling RLS on the join table + adding a policy. Migration file content:

```sql
-- migrations/20260605120003_projects_and_collaborators.sql
CREATE TABLE projects (
  id uuid PRIMARY KEY,
  owner_id uuid NOT NULL,
  name text NOT NULL
);

ALTER TABLE projects ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE projects FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

CREATE POLICY owner_sees_project ON projects
  FOR SELECT USING (owner_id = auth.uid())
  WITH CHECK (owner_id = auth.uid());

CREATE TABLE project_collaborators (
  project_id uuid REFERENCES projects(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  user_id uuid NOT NULL,
  role text DEFAULT 'viewer',
  PRIMARY KEY (project_id, user_id)
);

-- NOTE: no RLS enabled on project_collaborators (intentional gap)
```

Auth model: `auth.uid()`. Tenant scope: per-user.
